HOUSE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION NO. 102
BY REPRESENTATIVE CARVER
ELDERLY: Continues the Senior Task Force on Fraud Prevention
1 A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION
2 To continue the Senior Task Force on Fraud Prevention created in the 2025 Regular Session
3 of the Legislature of Louisiana pursuant to House Concurrent Resolution No. 53 to
4 study the occurrence and effect of fraud committed against elderly persons in
5 Louisiana.
6 WHEREAS, as technology and automation evolves, a growing fraud industry is
7 stealing billions from consumers each year; and
8 WHEREAS, over eighty-four thousand Louisianans were victims of fraud and scams
9 resulting in eighty-nine million four hundred thousand dollars in losses in 2024; and
10 WHEREAS, every two seconds, a Louisianan becomes a victim of identity theft,
11 highlighting the urgent and pervasive nature of this crime; and
12 WHEREAS, older adults are often prime targets for scammers due to factors such
13 as accumulated savings, limited familiarity with digital technology, and increased social
14 isolation, which can heighten their vulnerability to financial exploitation and identity theft;
15 and
16 WHEREAS, according to a recent AARP Fraud Watch Network report, over one
17 hundred forty-one million adults, representing forty-two percent of the United States
18 population, have had money or sensitive information stolen through fraud; and
19 WHEREAS, data from the Federal Trade Commission indicates that while younger
20 adults aged twenty to twenty-nine report losing money to fraud in forty-four percent of
21 cases, older adults aged seventy to seventy-nine report financial losses in twenty-four
