1 percent of cases, and those aged eighty and older experience the highest median losses of
2 any age group; and
3 WHEREAS, although older adults may report fraud less frequently than younger
4 individuals, the financial impact of these crimes is often far more devastating for seniors,
5 with significantly higher median losses among those aged seventy and above.
6 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the Legislature of Louisiana does hereby
7 continue the Senior Task Force on Fraud Prevention, and may propose recommendations,
8 together with specific proposals for legislation. Any recommendations or proposals shall
9 be submitted by written report to the legislature and to the David R. Poynter Legislative
10 Research Library as required by R.S. 24:771 and 772.
11 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that, with the following exceptions, the membership
12 and duties of the task force shall continue as provided in House Concurrent Resolution No.
13 53 of the 2025 Regular Session of the Legislature of Louisiana.
14 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the membership of the task force shall also
15 include all of the following:
16 (1) One designee appointed by the United States Attorney's Office, Western District
17 of Louisiana.
18 (2) One designee appointed by the United States Attorney's Office, Eastern District
19 of Louisiana.
20 (3) One designee appointed by the Louisiana Bankers Association.
21 (4) The executive director of the office of elderly affairs in the office of the governor
22 or his designee.
23 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that each designating authority shall submit the
24 names of designees to the task force to the office of attorney general no later than July 1,
25 2026.
26 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall convene for its first meeting
27 no later than August 1, 2026, at the call of AARP of Louisiana.
28 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Rules of Order of the House of
29 Representatives or applicable Joint Rules shall apply to all meetings of the task force.
